households and retinues, Edward II's relationship with Piers Gaveston, court venues and the image presented by royal justice, the pattern of clergy ordinations, and the Despensers' patronage of Tewkesbury Abbey. Three essays deal with aspects of Richard II's reign, two reassessing the so-called `tyranny', and a third looking at the inter-relation of English and Irish politics. The final essays look at general but related themes, the administration of royal justice and the role of morality in the exercise of public office. NIGEL SAUL is Professor of Medieval History at Royal Holloway, University of London. CONTRIBUTORS: ALISON MARSHALL, ELIZABETH H. WILL, JOCHEN BURGTORF, DAVID ROBINSON, MARTYN LAWRENCE, PETER CROOKS, G.B. STOW, TERRY JONES, ANTHONY MUSSON, CHRISTOPHER FLETCHER  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aBurgtorf, Jochen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrooks, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, C. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Terry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Martyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMusson, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaul, Nigel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStow, G. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStow, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g